# 20-code-quality-rules.mdc

## Readability and maintainability
- Write code that is obvious to the next developer.
- Prefer clear names over clever implementations.
- Prefer explicit control flow over overly compact expressions.
- Functions should do one thing and have clear inputs/outputs.
- Avoid deep nesting when early returns improve readability.

## Reuse and abstraction
- Extract shared logic only after repetition is real, not speculative.
- Prefer composition over inheritance unless the codebase already uses inheritance heavily.
- Keep abstractions lightweight and justified by repeated use.

## Dependency discipline
- Do not add new dependencies unless clearly necessary.
- If a dependency is proposed, explain why it is necessary before adding it.
- Prefer existing libraries or native platform features before introducing new packages.
- Avoid adding dependencies for simple or trivial functionality.
- Prefer well-maintained, widely used libraries when dependencies are required.
- Avoid redundant libraries that duplicate existing functionality in the codebase.
- Justify any new dependency with a clear reason.
- When unsure, default to not adding a dependency.

## Types and contracts
- Use strong typing where the stack supports it.
- Avoid `any`/loosely typed escape hatches unless unavoidable and documented.
- Validate boundaries between systems: API inputs, database records, external service payloads, and file parsing.

## Error handling
- Fail loudly in development and predictably in production.
- Do not swallow errors.
- Return actionable error messages internally, but do not leak sensitive details externally.
- Handle retries intentionally; never add blind retries around unsafe operations.

## Comments and docs
- Comment the “why,” not the obvious “what.”
- Update related docs when behavior, setup, or architecture changes.
- Remove dead code instead of leaving large commented blocks.
